"explore.mock.efficiency_desc" = "Heart rate and breathing trends were both steady, which usually means the parasympathetic system is dominant and the body can relax naturally without extra “slow down” effort.\n\nWithin the 30 minutes before sleep, heart rate and breathing stayed relatively stable or gently declined. This often correlates with shorter sleep latency and is a common physiological signal used to judge readiness for sleep.";
"explore.mock.structure_desc" = "These data don’t suggest a structural abnormality. Last night’s sleep stages were intact, but each key stage was more fragmented—typical of nights with multiple interruptions, where deep sleep and REM are compressed.\n\nThis is one of the most common, and most repairable, patterns on stressed nights.";
"explore.mock.fluctuation_desc" = "Together, these signals indicate a highly reactive nervous system at night—more sensitive to external stimuli and internal anxiety. At 03:25, Mindora detected heart-rate and breathing fluctuations, and the awakening exceeded the physiological adjustment threshold. Mindora initiated a 15-minute intervention using the low-frequency, continuous waves of “Amalfi Coast Breeze,” helping the nervous system shift back to parasympathetic dominance so you could settle and fall asleep again within 15 minutes.";
"explore.mock.preference_desc" = "Last night, you fell asleep in the “Cocos Island Moonlight Drift” environment—an ocean-embracing soundscape with pink and brown noise.\n\nIts structure centers on low-frequency, continuous ocean waves with a steady rhythm and no sharp spikes—an environment that doesn’t demand attention but stays present.\n\nResearch shows that low-frequency, continuous natural soundscapes reduce alertness to environmental changes and lessen pre-sleep safety checking. The slow ocean rhythm also syncs more easily with breathing, helping the nervous system shift into rest.\n\nYour body’s response confirmed this: sleep onset took 15 minutes, pre-sleep heart rate was about 68 bpm, and breathing rate was 15 breaths/min—relaxed and steady. Night awakenings were mostly turns, without clear physiological spikes, more like natural transitions between stages.\n\nYou adapt well to low-frequency, continuous natural-water rhythms. This environment suits a gradual “letting go” at sleep onset rather than a strong guided drop-off.";
"explore.mock.advice_desc" = "Across several nights, your overall sleep has been stable. To further reduce night fluctuations, try lowering external stimulation in the hour before bed or ending audio playback slightly earlier over the next few nights.\n\nSleep isn’t a straight line—it’s a system that can be disturbed and self-repair. Tracking these changes isn’t to judge, but to find the easiest, most stable sleep pattern for you.\n\nLast night, your body did that.";
